                                            <h3 class="hed"><a href="/2017/11/the-ceo-of-kronos-on-launching-an-unlimited-vacation-policy">The CEO of Kronos on Launching an Unlimited Vacation Policy</a></h3>
                                            <div class="mbl">
                                                <span class="topic">Leadership & Managing people</span> <span class="content-type">Magazine Article</span> <span class="byline"><ul class="byline-list"><li>Aron Ain</li></ul></span>
                                            </div>
                                            <p>Technology has made it possible for employees to be plugged in around the clock, even when they&#8217;re &#8220;on vacation.&#8221; In view of this reality, Kronos launched its open vacation policy in early 2016. To Ain&#8217;s surprise, some employees were very unhappy about it, largely for three reasons: Because the new policy required individuals to work out time off with their supervisors, some managers thought their jobs would become more difficult. Some employees who had been banking unused vacation time resented the loss of a bundle of cash when they retired. And some felt that it was unfair for new hires to get as much vacation as they themselves had earned over time. But Kronos now considers the switch a success&#8212;and 2016 was financially the company&#8217;s best year ever.</p>

